@node "Invoking gcj" "gcj.guide/Invoking gcj"
@next "Compatibility"
@prev "GNU Free Documentation License"
@toc "Main"

Invoking gcj
************

As @{b}gcj@{ub} is just another front end to @{b}gcc@{ub}, it supports many of the same
options as gcc.  See @{"gcc.guide/Option Summary" link "gcc.guide/Option Summary"}.  This manual only
documents the options specific to @{b}gcj@{ub}.


 @{" Input and output files " link "Input and output files"}  
 @{" Input Options        " link "Input Options"}  How gcj finds files
 @{" Encodings            " link "Encodings"}  Options controlling source file encoding
 @{" Warnings             " link "Warnings"}  Options controlling warnings specific to gcj
 @{" Code Generation      " link "Code Generation"}  Options controlling the output of gcj
 @{" Configure-time Options " link "Configure-time Options"}  Options you won't use

@endnode

@node "Input and output files" "gcj.guide/Input and output files"
@next "Input Options"
@toc "Invoking gcj"

Input and output files
======================

A @{b}gcj@{ub} command is like a @{b}gcc@{ub} command, in that it consists of a number of
options and file names.  The following kinds of input file names are
supported:

@{b}FILE.java@{ub}
     Java source files.

@{b}FILE.class@{ub}
     Java bytecode files.

@{b}FILE.zip@{ub}
@{b}FILE.jar@{ub}
     An archive containing one or more @{b}.class@{ub} files, all of which are
     compiled.  The archive may be compressed.  Files in an archive
     which don't end with @{b}.class@{ub} are treated as resource files; they
     are copmiled into the resulting object file as @{b}core:@{ub} URLs.

@{b}\@FILE@{ub}
     A file containing a whitespace-separated list of input file names.
     (Currently, these must all be @{b}.java@{ub} source files, but that may
     change.)  Each named file is compiled, just as if it had been on
     the command line.

@{b}LIBRARY.a@{ub}
@{b}LIBRARY.so@{ub}
@{b}-lLIBNAME@{ub}
     Libraries to use when linking.  See the @{b}gcc@{ub} manual.

   You can specify more than one input file on the @{b}gcj@{ub} command line, in
which case they will all be compiled.  If you specify a @{b}-o FILENAME@{ub}
option, all the input files will be compiled together, producing a
single output file, named FILENAME.  This is allowed even when using @{b}-S@{ub}
or @{b}-c@{ub}, but not when using @{b}-C@{ub} or @{b}--resource@{ub}.  (This is an extension
beyond the what plain @{b}gcc@{ub} allows.)  (If more than one input file is
specified, all must currently be @{b}.java@{ub} files, though we hope to fix
this.)

@endnode

@node "Input Options" "gcj.guide/Input Options"
@next "Encodings"
@prev "Input and output files"
@toc "Invoking gcj"

Input Options
=============

@{b}gcj@{ub} has options to control where it looks to find files it needs.  For
instance, @{b}gcj@{ub} might need to load a class that is referenced by the file
it has been asked to compile.  Like other compilers for the Java
language, @{b}gcj@{ub} has a notion of a @{i}class path@{ui}.  There are several options
and environment variables which can be used to manipulate the class
path.  When @{b}gcj@{ub} looks for a given class, it searches the class path
looking for matching @{b}.class@{ub} or @{b}.java@{ub} file.  @{b}gcj@{ub} comes with a built-in
class path which points at the installed @{b}libgcj.jar@{ub}, a file which
contains all the standard classes.

   In the below, a directory or path component can refer either to an
actual directory on the filesystem, or to a @{b}.zip@{ub} or @{b}.jar@{ub} file, which
@{b}gcj@{ub} will search as if it is a directory.

@{b}-IDIR@{ub}
     All directories specified by @{b}-I@{ub} are kept in order and prepended to
     the class path constructed from all the other options.  Unless
     compatibility with tools like @{b}javac@{ub} is important, we recommend
     always using @{b}-I@{ub} instead of the other options for manipulating the
     class path.

@{b}--classpath=PATH@{ub}
     This sets the class path to PATH, a colon-separated list of paths
     (on Windows-based systems, a semicolon-separate list of paths).
     This does not override the builtin ("boot") search path.

@{b}--CLASSPATH=PATH@{ub}
     Deprecated synonym for @{b}--classpath@{ub}.

@{b}--bootclasspath=PATH@{ub}
     Where to find the standard builtin classes, such as
     @{b}java.lang.String@{ub}.

@{b}--extdirs=PATH@{ub}
     For each directory in the PATH, place the contents of that
     directory at the end of the class path.

@{b}CLASSPATH@{ub}
     This is an environment variable which holds a list of paths.

   The final class path is constructed like so:

   * First come all directories specified via @{b}-I@{ub}.

   * If @{b}--classpath@{ub} is specified, its value is appended.  Otherwise, if
     the @{b}CLASSPATH@{ub} environment variable is specified, then its value is
     appended.  Otherwise, the current directory (@{b}"."@{ub}) is appended.

   * If @{b}--bootclasspath@{ub} was specified, append its value.  Otherwise,
     append the built-in system directory, @{b}libgcj.jar@{ub}.

   * Finally, if @{b}--extdirs@{ub} was specified, append the contents of the
     specified directories at the end of the class path.  Otherwise,
     append the contents of the built-in extdirs at
     @{b}$(prefix)/share/java/ext@{ub}.

   The classfile built by @{b}gcj@{ub} for the class @{b}java.lang.Object@{ub} (and
placed in @{b}libgcj.jar@{ub}) contains a special zero length attribute
@{b}gnu.gcj.gcj-compiled@{ub}. The compiler looks for this attribute when
loading @{b}java.lang.Object@{ub} and will report an error if it isn't found,
unless it compiles to bytecode (the option
@{b}-fforce-classes-archive-check@{ub} can be used to override this behavior in
this particular case.)

@{b}-fforce-classes-archive-check@{ub}
     This forces the compiler to always check for the special zero
     length attribute @{b}gnu.gcj.gcj-compiled@{ub} in @{b}java.lang.Object@{ub} and
     issue an error if it isn't found.

@endnode

@node "Encodings" "gcj.guide/Encodings"
@next "Warnings"
@prev "Input Options"
@toc "Invoking gcj"

Encodings
=========

The Java programming language uses Unicode throughout.  In an effort to
integrate well with other locales, @{b}gcj@{ub} allows @{b}.java@{ub} files to be written
using almost any encoding.  @{b}gcj@{ub} knows how to convert these encodings
into its internal encoding at compile time.

   You can use the @{b}--encoding=NAME@{ub} option to specify an encoding (of a
particular character set) to use for source files.  If this is not
specified, the default encoding comes from your current locale.  If
your host system has insufficient locale support, then @{b}gcj@{ub} assumes the
default encoding to be the @{b}UTF-8@{ub} encoding of Unicode.

   To implement @{b}--encoding@{ub}, @{b}gcj@{ub} simply uses the host platform's @{b}iconv@{ub}
conversion routine.  This means that in practice @{b}gcj@{ub} is limited by the
capabilities of the host platform.

   The names allowed for the argument @{b}--encoding@{ub} vary from platform to
platform (since they are not standardized anywhere).  However, @{b}gcj@{ub}
implements the encoding named @{b}UTF-8@{ub} internally, so if you choose to use
this for your source files you can be assured that it will work on
every host.

@endnode

@node "Warnings" "gcj.guide/Warnings"
@next "Code Generation"
@prev "Encodings"
@toc "Invoking gcj"

Warnings
========

@{b}gcj@{ub} implements several warnings.  As with other generic @{b}gcc@{ub} warnings,
if an option of the form @{b}-Wfoo@{ub} enables a warning, then @{b}-Wno-foo@{ub} will
disable it.  Here we've chosen to document the form of the warning
which will have an effect - the default being the opposite of what is
listed.

@{b}-Wredundant-modifiers@{ub}
     With this flag, @{b}gcj@{ub} will warn about redundant modifiers.  For
     instance, it will warn if an interface method is declared @{b}public@{ub}.

@{b}-Wextraneous-semicolon@{ub}
     This causes @{b}gcj@{ub} to warn about empty statements.  Empty statements
     have been deprecated.

@{b}-Wno-out-of-date@{ub}
     This option will cause @{b}gcj@{ub} not to warn when a source file is newer
     than its matching class file.  By default @{b}gcj@{ub} will warn about this.

@{b}-Wno-deprecated@{ub}
     Warn if a deprecated class, method, or field is referred to.

@{b}-Wunused@{ub}
     This is the same as @{b}gcc@{ub}'s @{b}-Wunused@{ub}.

@{b}-Wall@{ub}
     This is the same as @{b}-Wredundant-modifiers -Wextraneous-semicolon
     -Wunused@{ub}.

@endnode

@node "Code Generation" "gcj.guide/Code Generation"
@next "Configure-time Options"
@prev "Warnings"
@toc "Invoking gcj"

Code Generation
===============

In addition to the many @{b}gcc@{ub} options controlling code generation, @{b}gcj@{ub}
has several options specific to itself.

@{b}--main=CLASSNAME@{ub}
     This option is used when linking to specify the name of the class
     whose @{b}main@{ub} method should be invoked when the resulting executable
     is run.  (1)

@{b}-DNAME[=VALUE]@{ub}
     This option can only be used with @{b}--main@{ub}.  It defines a system
     property named NAME with value VALUE.  If VALUE is not specified
     then it defaults to the empty string.  These system properties are
     initialized at the program's startup and can be retrieved at
     runtime using the @{b}java.lang.System.getProperty@{ub} method.

@{b}-C@{ub}
     This option is used to tell @{b}gcj@{ub} to generate bytecode (@{b}.class@{ub}
     files) rather than object code.

@{b}--resource RESOURCE-NAME@{ub}
     This option is used to tell @{b}gcj@{ub} to compile the contents of a given
     file to object code so it may be accessed at runtime with the core
     protocol handler as @{b}core:/RESOURCE-NAME@{ub}.  Note that RESOURCE-NAME
     is the name of the resource as found at runtime; for instance, it
     could be used in a call to @{b}ResourceBundle.getBundle@{ub}.  The actual
     file name to be compiled this way must be specified separately.

@{b}-d DIRECTORY@{ub}
     When used with @{b}-C@{ub}, this causes all generated @{b}.class@{ub} files to be
     put in the appropriate subdirectory of DIRECTORY.  By default they
     will be put in subdirectories of the current working directory.

@{b}-fno-bounds-check@{ub}
     By default, @{b}gcj@{ub} generates code which checks the bounds of all
     array indexing operations.  With this option, these checks are
     omitted, which can improve performance for code that uses arrays
     extensively.  Note that this can result in unpredictable behavior
     if the code in question actually does violate array bounds
     constraints.  It is safe to use this option if you are sure that
     your code will never throw an @{b}ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException@{ub}.

@{b}-fno-store-check@{ub}
     Don't generate array store checks.  When storing objects into
     arrays, a runtime check is normally generated in order to ensure
     that the object is assignment compatible with the component type
     of the array (which may not be known at compile-time).  With this
     option, these checks are omitted.  This can improve performance
     for code which stores objects into arrays frequently.  It is safe
     to use this option if you are sure your code will never throw an
     @{b}ArrayStoreException@{ub}.

@{b}-fjni@{ub}
     With @{b}gcj@{ub} there are two options for writing native methods: CNI and
     JNI.  By default @{b}gcj@{ub} assumes you are using CNI.  If you are
     compiling a class with native methods, and these methods are
     implemented using JNI, then you must use @{b}-fjni@{ub}.  This option causes
     @{b}gcj@{ub} to generate stubs which will invoke the underlying JNI methods.

@{b}-fno-assert@{ub}
     Don't recognize the @{b}assert@{ub} keyword.  This is for compatibility
     with older versions of the language specification.

@{b}-fno-optimize-static-class-initialization@{ub}
     When the optimization level is greater or equal to @{b}-O2@{ub}, @{b}gcj@{ub} will
     try to optimize the way calls into the runtime are made to
     initialize static classes upon their first use (this optimization
     isn't carried out if @{b}-C@{ub} was specified.) When compiling to native
     code, @{b}-fno-optimize-static-class-initialization@{ub} will turn this
     optimization off, regardless of the optimization level in use.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1) The linker by default looks for a global function named @{b}main@{ub}.
Since Java does not have global functions, and a collection of Java
classes may have more than one class with a @{b}main@{ub} method, you need to
let the linker know which of those @{b}main@{ub} methods it should invoke when
starting the application.

@endnode

@node "Configure-time Options" "gcj.guide/Configure-time Options"
@prev "Code Generation"
@toc "Invoking gcj"

Configure-time Options
======================

Some @{b}gcj@{ub} code generations options affect the resulting ABI, and so can
only be meaningfully given when @{b}libgcj@{ub}, the runtime package, is
configured.  @{b}libgcj@{ub} puts the appropriate options from this group into a
@{b}spec@{ub} file which is read by @{b}gcj@{ub}.  These options are listed here for
completeness; if you are using @{b}libgcj@{ub} then you won't want to touch
these options.

@{b}-fuse-boehm-gc@{ub}
     This enables the use of the Boehm GC bitmap marking code.  In
     particular this causes @{b}gcj@{ub} to put an object marking descriptor
     into each vtable.

@{b}-fhash-synchronization@{ub}
     By default, synchronization data (the data used for @{b}synchronize@{ub},
     @{b}wait@{ub}, and @{b}notify@{ub}) is pointed to by a word in each object.  With
     this option @{b}gcj@{ub} assumes that this information is stored in a hash
     table and not in the object itself.

@{b}-fuse-divide-subroutine@{ub}
     On some systems, a library routine is called to perform integer
     division.  This is required to get exception handling correct when
     dividing by zero.

@{b}-fcheck-references@{ub}
     On some systems it's necessary to insert inline checks whenever
     accessing an object via a reference.  On other systems you won't
     need this because null pointer accesses are caught automatically
     by the processor.

@endnode

@node "Compatibility" "gcj.guide/Compatibility"
@next "Invoking gcjh"
@prev "Invoking gcj"
@toc "Main"

Compatibility with the Java Platform
************************************

As we believe it is important that the Java platform not be fragmented,
@{b}gcj@{ub} and @{b}libgcj@{ub} try to conform to the relevant Java specifications.
However, limited manpower and incomplete and unclear documentation work
against us.  So, there are caveats to using @{b}gcj@{ub}.


 @{" Limitations                " link "Limitations"}  
 @{" Extensions                 " link "Extensions"}

@endnode

@node "Limitations" "gcj.guide/Limitations"
@next "Extensions"
@toc "Compatibility"

Standard features not yet supported
===================================

This list of compatibility issues is by no means complete.

   * @{b}gcj@{ub} implements the JDK 1.2 language.  It supports inner classes
     and the new 1.4 @{b}assert@{ub} keyword.  It does not yet support the Java 2
     @{b}strictfp@{ub} keyword (it recognizes the keyword but ignores it).

   * @{b}libgcj@{ub} is largely compatible with the JDK 1.2 libraries.  However,
     @{b}libgcj@{ub} is missing many packages, most notably @{b}java.awt@{ub}.  There are
     also individual missing classes and methods.  We currently do not
     have a list showing differences between @{b}libgcj@{ub} and the Java 2
     platform.

   * Sometimes the @{b}libgcj@{ub} implementation of a method or class differs
     from the JDK implementation.  This is not always a bug.  Still, if
     it affects you, it probably makes sense to report it so that we
     can discuss the appropriate response.

   * @{b}gcj@{ub} does not currently allow for piecemeal replacement of
     components within @{b}libgcj@{ub}. Unfortunately, programmers often want to
     use newer versions of certain packages, such as those provided by
     the Apache Software Foundation's Jakarta project.  This has forced
     us to place the @{b}org.w3c.dom@{ub} and @{b}org.xml.sax@{ub} packages into their
     own libraries, separate from @{b}libgcj@{ub}.  If you intend to use these
     classes, you must link them explicitly with @{b}-l-org-w3c-dom@{ub} and
     @{b}-l-org-xml-sax@{ub}.  Future versions of @{b}gcj@{ub} may not have this
     restriction.

@endnode

@node "Extensions" "gcj.guide/Extensions"
@prev "Limitations"
@toc "Compatibility"

Extra features unique to gcj
============================

The main feature of @{b}gcj@{ub} is that it can compile programs written in the
Java programming language to native code.  Most extensions that have
been added are to facilitate this functionality.

   * @{b}gcj@{ub} makes it easy and efficient to mix code written in Java and
     C++.  See @{"About CNI" link "About CNI"}, for more info on how to use this in your
     programs.

   * When you compile your classes into a shared library they can be
     automatically loaded by the @{b}libgcj@{ub} system classloader.  When
     trying to load a class @{b}gnu.pkg.SomeClass@{ub} the system classloader
     will first try to load the shared library
     @{b}lib-gnu-pkg-SomeClass.so@{ub}, if that fails to load the class then it
     will try to load @{b}lib-gnu-pkg.so@{ub} and finally when the class is
     still not loaded it will try to load @{b}lib-gnu.so@{ub}.  Note that all @{b}.@{ub}s
     will be transformed into @{b}-@{ub}s and that searching for inner classes
     starts with their outermost outer class.  If the class cannot be
     found this way the system classloader tries to use the @{b}libgcj@{ub}
     bytecode interpreter to load the class from the standard
     classpath.  This process can be controlled to some degree via the
     @{b}gnu.gcj.runtime.VMClassLoader.library_control@{ub} property; See
     @{"libgcj Runtime Properties" link "libgcj Runtime Properties"}.

   * @{b}libgcj@{ub} includes a special @{b}gcjlib@{ub} URL type.  A URL of this form is
     like a @{b}jar@{ub} URL, and looks like
     @{b}gcjlib:/path/to/shared/library.so!/path/to/resource@{ub}.  An access to
     one of these URLs causes the shared library to be @{b}dlopen()@{ub}d, and
     then the resource is looked for in that library.  These URLs are
     most useful when used in conjunction with @{b}java.net.URLClassLoader@{ub}.
     Note that, due to implementation limitations, currently any such
     URL can be accessed by only one class loader, and libraries are
     never unloaded.  This means some care must be exercised to make
     sure that a @{b}gcjlib@{ub} URL is not accessed by more than one class
     loader at once.  In a future release this limitation will be
     lifted, and such libraries will be mapped privately.

   * A program compiled by @{b}gcj@{ub} will examine the @{b}GCJ_PROPERTIES@{ub}
     environment variable and change its behavior in some ways.  In
     particular @{b}GCJ_PROPERTIES@{ub} holds a list of assignments to global
     properties, such as would be set with the @{b}-D@{ub} option to @{b}java@{ub}.  For
     instance, @{b}java.compiler=gcj@{ub} is a valid (but currently meaningless)
     setting.


@endnode

@node "Invoking gcjh" "gcj.guide/Invoking gcjh"
@next "Invoking jv-scan"
@prev "Compatibility"
@toc "Main"

Invoking gcjh
*************

The @{b}gcjh@{ub} program is used to generate header files from class files.  It
can generate both CNI and JNI header files, as well as stub
implementation files which can be used as a basis for implementing the
required native methods.

@{b}-stubs@{ub}
     This causes @{b}gcjh@{ub} to generate stub files instead of header files.
     By default the stub file will be named after the class, with a
     suffix of @{b}.cc@{ub}.  In JNI mode, the default output file will have the
     suffix @{b}.c@{ub}.

@{b}-jni@{ub}
     This tells @{b}gcjh@{ub} to generate a JNI header or stub.  By default, CNI
     headers are generated.

@{b}-add TEXT@{ub}
     Inserts TEXT into the class body.  This is ignored in JNI mode.

@{b}-append TEXT@{ub}
     Inserts TEXT into the header file after the class declaration.
     This is ignored in JNI mode.

@{b}-friend TEXT@{ub}
     Inserts TEXT into the class as a @{b}friend@{ub} declaration.  This is
     ignored in JNI mode.

@{b}-prepend TEXT@{ub}
     Inserts TEXT into the header file before the class declaration.
     This is ignored in JNI mode.

@{b}--classpath=PATH@{ub}
@{b}--CLASSPATH=PATH@{ub}
@{b}-IDIRECTORY@{ub}
@{b}-d DIRECTORY@{ub}
@{b}-o FILE@{ub}
     These options are all identical to the corresponding @{b}gcj@{ub} options.

@{b}-o FILE@{ub}
     Sets the output file name.  This cannot be used if there is more
     than one class on the command line.

@{b}-td DIRECTORY@{ub}
     Sets the name of the directory to use for temporary files.

@{b}-M@{ub}
     Print all dependencies to stdout; suppress ordinary output.

@{b}-MM@{ub}
     Print non-system dependencies to stdout; suppress ordinary output.

@{b}-MD@{ub}
     Print all dependencies to stdout.

@{b}-MMD@{ub}
     Print non-system dependencies to stdout.

@{b}--help@{ub}
     Print help about @{b}gcjh@{ub} and exit.  No further processing is done.

@{b}--version@{ub}
     Print version information for @{b}gcjh@{ub} and exit.  No further
     processing is done.

@{b}-v, --verbose@{ub}
     Print extra information while running.

   All remaining options are considered to be names of classes.

@endnode

@node "Invoking jv-scan" "gcj.guide/Invoking jv-scan"
@next "Invoking jcf-dump"
@prev "Invoking gcjh"
@toc "Main"

Invoking jv-scan
****************

The @{b}jv-scan@{ub} program can be used to print information about a Java
source file (@{b}.java@{ub} file).

@{b}--no-assert@{ub}
     Don't recognize the @{b}assert@{ub} keyword, for backwards compatibility
     with older versions of the language specification.

@{b}--complexity@{ub}
     This prints a complexity measure, related to cyclomatic
     complexity, for each input file.

@{b}--encoding=NAME@{ub}
     This works like the corresponding @{b}gcj@{ub} option.

@{b}--print-main@{ub}
     This prints the name of the class in this file containing a @{b}main@{ub}
     method.

@{b}--list-class@{ub}
     This lists the names of all classes defined in the input files.

@{b}--list-filename@{ub}
     If @{b}--list-class@{ub} is given, this option causes @{b}jv-scan@{ub} to also print
     the name of the file in which each class was found.

@{b}-o FILE@{ub}
     Print output to the named file.

@{b}--help@{ub}
     Print help, then exit.

@{b}--version@{ub}
     Print version number, then exit.

@endnode

@node "Invoking jcf-dump" "gcj.guide/Invoking jcf-dump"
@next "Invoking gij"
@prev "Invoking jv-scan"
@toc "Main"

Invoking jcf-dump
*****************

This is a class file examiner, similar to @{b}javap@{ub}.  It will print
information about a number of classes, which are specified by class name
or file name.

@{b}-c@{ub}
     Disassemble method bodies.  By default method bodies are not
     printed.

@{b}--javap@{ub}
     Generate output in @{b}javap@{ub} format.  The implementation of this
     feature is very incomplete.

@{b}--classpath=PATH@{ub}
@{b}--CLASSPATH=PATH@{ub}
@{b}-IDIRECTORY@{ub}
@{b}-o FILE@{ub}
     These options as the same as the corresponding @{b}gcj@{ub} options.

@{b}--help@{ub}
     Print help, then exit.

@{b}--version@{ub}
     Print version number, then exit.

@{b}-v, --verbose@{ub}
     Print extra information while running.

@endnode

@node "Invoking gij" "gcj.guide/Invoking gij"
@next "Invoking jv-convert"
@prev "Invoking jcf-dump"
@toc "Main"

Invoking gij
************

@{b}gij@{ub} is a Java bytecode interpreter included with @{b}libgcj@{ub}.  @{b}gij@{ub} is not
available on every platform; porting it requires a small amount of
assembly programming which has not been done for all the targets
supported by @{b}gcj@{ub}.

   The primary argument to @{b}gij@{ub} is the name of a class or, with @{b}-jar@{ub}, a
jar file.  Options before this argument are interpreted by @{b}gij@{ub};
remaining options are passed to the interpreted program.

   If a class name is specified and this class does not have a @{b}main@{ub}
method with the appropriate signature (a @{b}static void@{ub} method with a
@{b}String[]@{ub} as its sole argument), then @{b}gij@{ub} will print an error and exit.

   If a jar file is specified then @{b}gij@{ub} will use information in it to
determine which class' @{b}main@{ub} method will be invoked.

   @{b}gij@{ub} will invoke the @{b}main@{ub} method with all the remaining command-line
options.

   Note that @{b}gij@{ub} is not limited to interpreting code.  Because @{b}libgcj@{ub}
includes a class loader which can dynamically load shared objects, it
is possible to give @{b}gij@{ub} the name of a class which has been compiled and
put into a shared library on the class path.

@{b}-cp PATH@{ub}
@{b}-classpath PATH@{ub}
     Set the initial class path.  The class path is used for finding
     class and resource files.  If specified, this option overrides the
     @{b}CLASSPATH@{ub} environment variable.  Note that this option is ignored
     if @{b}-jar@{ub} is used.

@{b}-DNAME[=VALUE]@{ub}
     This defines a system property named NAME with value VALUE.  If
     VALUE is not specified then it defaults to the empty string.
     These system properties are initialized at the program's startup
     and can be retrieved at runtime using the
     @{b}java.lang.System.getProperty@{ub} method.

@{b}-ms=NUMBER@{ub}
     This sets the initial heap size.

@{b}-mx=NUMBER@{ub}
     This sets the maximum heap size.

@{b}-X@{ub}
@{b}-XARGUMENT@{ub}
     Supplying @{b}-X@{ub} by itself will cause @{b}gij@{ub} to list all the supported @{b}-X@{ub}
     options.  Currently there are none.  Unrecognized @{b}-X@{ub} options are
     ignored, for compatibility with other runtimes.

@{b}-jar@{ub}
     This indicates that the name passed to @{b}gij@{ub} should be interpreted
     as the name of a jar file, not a class.

@{b}--help@{ub}
@{b}-?@{ub}
     Print help, then exit.

@{b}--showversion@{ub}
     Print version number and continue.

@{b}--version@{ub}
     Print version number, then exit.

@endnode

@node "Invoking jv-convert" "gcj.guide/Invoking jv-convert"
@next "Invoking rmic"
@prev "Invoking gij"
@toc "Main"

Invoking jv-convert
*******************

@{b}jv-convert@{ub} [@{b}OPTION@{ub}] ... [INPUTFILE [OUTPUTFILE]]

   @{b}jv-convert@{ub} is a utility included with @{b}libgcj@{ub} which converts a file
from one encoding to another.  It is similar to the Unix @{b}iconv@{ub} utility.

   The encodings supported by @{b}jv-convert@{ub} are platform-dependent.
Currently there is no way to get a list of all supported encodings.

@{b}--encoding NAME@{ub}
@{b}--from NAME@{ub}
     Use NAME as the input encoding.  The default is the current
     locale's encoding.

@{b}--to NAME@{ub}
     Use NAME as the output encoding.  The default is the @{b}JavaSrc@{ub}
     encoding; this is ASCII with @{b}\\u@{ub} escapes for non-ASCII characters.

@{b}-i FILE@{ub}
     Read from FILE.  The default is to read from standard input.

@{b}-o FILE@{ub}
     Write to FILE.  The default is to write to standard output.

@{b}--reverse@{ub}
     Swap the input and output encodings.

@{b}--help@{ub}
     Print a help message, then exit.

@{b}--version@{ub}
     Print version information, then exit.

@endnode

@node "Invoking rmic" "gcj.guide/Invoking rmic"
@next "Invoking rmiregistry"
@prev "Invoking jv-convert"
@toc "Main"

Invoking rmic
*************

@{b}rmic@{ub} [@{b}OPTION@{ub}] ... CLASS ...

   @{b}rmic@{ub} is a utility included with @{b}libgcj@{ub} which generates stubs for
remote objects.

   Note that this program isn't yet fully compatible with the JDK @{b}rmic@{ub}.
Some options, such as @{b}-classpath@{ub}, are recognized but currently
ignored.  We have left these options undocumented for now.

   Long options can also be given with a GNU-style leading @{b}--@{ub}.  For
instance, @{b}--help@{ub} is accepted.

@{b}-keep@{ub}
@{b}-keepgenerated@{ub}
     By default, @{b}rmic@{ub} deletes intermediate files.  Either of these
     options causes it not to delete such files.

@{b}-v1.1@{ub}
     Cause @{b}rmic@{ub} to create stubs and skeletons for the 1.1 protocol
     version.

@{b}-vcompat@{ub}
     Cause @{b}rmic@{ub} to create stubs and skeletons compatible with both the
     1.1 and 1.2 protocol versions.  This is the default.

@{b}-v1.2@{ub}
     Cause @{b}rmic@{ub} to create stubs and skeletons for the 1.2 protocol
     version.

@{b}-nocompile@{ub}
     Don't compile the generated files.

@{b}-verbose@{ub}
     Print information about what @{b}rmic@{ub} is doing.

@{b}-d DIRECTORY@{ub}
     Put output files in DIRECTORY.  By default the files are put in
     the current working directory.

@{b}-help@{ub}
     Print a help message, then exit.

@{b}-version@{ub}
     Print version information, then exit.

@endnode

@node "Invoking rmiregistry" "gcj.guide/Invoking rmiregistry"
@next "About CNI"
@prev "Invoking rmic"
@toc "Main"

Invoking rmiregistry
********************

@{b}rmic@{ub} [@{b}OPTION@{ub}] ... [PORT]

   @{b}rmiregistry@{ub} starts a remote object registry on the current host.  If
no port number is specified, then port 1099 is used.

@{b}--help@{ub}
     Print a help message, then exit.

@{b}--version@{ub}
     Print version information, then exit.

@endnode

@node "About CNI" "gcj.guide/About CNI"
@next "System properties"
@prev "Invoking rmiregistry"
@toc "Main"

About CNI
*********

This documents CNI, the Compiled Native Interface, which is is a
convenient way to write Java native methods using C++.  This is a more
efficient, more convenient, but less portable alternative to the
standard JNI (Java Native Interface).


 @{" Basic concepts             " link "Basic concepts"}  Introduction to using CNI.
 @{" Packages                   " link "Packages"}  How packages are mapped to C++.
 @{" Primitive types            " link "Primitive types"}  Handling Java types in C++.
 @{" Interfaces                 " link "Interfaces"}  How Java interfaces map to C++.
 @{" Objects and Classes        " link "Objects and Classes"}  C++ and Java classes.
 @{" Class Initialization       " link "Class Initialization"}  How objects are initialized.
 @{" Object allocation          " link "Object allocation"}  How to create Java objects in C++.
 @{" Arrays                     " link "Arrays"}  Dealing with Java arrays in C++.
 @{" Methods                    " link "Methods"}  Java methods in C++.
 @{" Strings                    " link "Strings"}  Information about Java Strings.
 @{" Mixing with C++            " link "Mixing with C++"}  How CNI can interoperate with C++.
 @{" Exception Handling         " link "Exception Handling"}  How exceptions are handled.
 @{" Synchronization            " link "Synchronization"}  Synchronizing between Java and C++.
 @{" Invocation                 " link "Invocation"}  Starting the Java runtime from C++.
 @{" Reflection                 " link "Reflection"}  Using reflection from C++.

@endnode

@node "Basic concepts" "gcj.guide/Basic concepts"
@next "Packages"
@toc "About CNI"

Basic concepts
==============

In terms of languages features, Java is mostly a subset of C++.  Java
has a few important extensions, plus a powerful standard class library,
but on the whole that does not change the basic similarity.  Java is a
hybrid object-oriented language, with a few native types, in addition
to class types.  It is class-based, where a class may have static as
well as per-object fields, and static as well as instance methods.
Non-static methods may be virtual, and may be overloaded.  Overloading
is resolved at compile time by matching the actual argument types
against the parameter types.  Virtual methods are implemented using
indirect calls through a dispatch table (virtual function table).
Objects are allocated on the heap, and initialized using a constructor
method.  Classes are organized in a package hierarchy.

   All of the listed attributes are also true of C++, though C++ has
extra features (for example in C++ objects may be allocated not just on
the heap, but also statically or in a local stack frame).  Because @{b}gcj@{ub}
uses the same compiler technology as G++ (the GNU C++ compiler), it is
possible to make the intersection of the two languages use the same ABI
(object representation and calling conventions).  The key idea in CNI
is that Java objects are C++ objects, and all Java classes are C++
classes (but not the other way around).  So the most important task in
integrating Java and C++ is to remove gratuitous incompatibilities.

   You write CNI code as a regular C++ source file.  (You do have to use
a Java/CNI-aware C++ compiler, specifically a recent version of G++.)

A CNI C++ source file must have:

     #include <gcj/cni.h>

and then must include one header file for each Java class it uses, e.g.:

     #include <java/lang/Character.h>
     #include <java/util/Date.h>
     #include <java/lang/IndexOutOfBoundsException.h>

These header files are automatically generated by @{b}gcjh@{ub}.

   CNI provides some functions and macros to make using Java objects and
primitive types from C++ easier.  In general, these CNI functions and
macros start with the @{b}Jv@{ub} prefix, for example the function
@{b}JvNewObjectArray@{ub}.  This convention is used to avoid conflicts with
other libraries.  Internal functions in CNI start with the prefix @{b}_Jv_@{ub}.
You should not call these; if you find a need to, let us know and we
will try to come up with an alternate solution.  (This manual lists
@{b}_Jv_AllocBytes@{ub} as an example; CNI should instead provide a @{b}JvAllocBytes@{ub}
function.)

Limitations
-----------

Whilst a Java class is just a C++ class that doesn't mean that you are
freed from the shackles of Java, a CNI C++ class must adhere to the
rules of the Java programming language.

   For example: it is not possible to declare a method in a CNI class
that will take a C string (@{b}char*@{ub}) as an argument, or to declare a
member variable of some non-Java datatype.

@endnode

@node "Packages" "gcj.guide/Packages"
@next "Primitive types"
@prev "Basic concepts"
@toc "About CNI"

Packages
========

The only global names in Java are class names, and packages.  A @{i}package@{ui}
can contain zero or more classes, and also zero or more sub-packages.
Every class belongs to either an unnamed package or a package that has
a hierarchical and globally unique name.

   A Java package is mapped to a C++ @{i}namespace@{ui}.  The Java class
@{b}java.lang.String@{ub} is in the package @{b}java.lang@{ub}, which is a sub-package of
@{b}java@{ub}.  The C++ equivalent is the class @{b}java::lang::String@{ub}, which is in
the namespace @{b}java::lang@{ub} which is in the namespace @{b}java@{ub}.

Here is how you could express this:

     (// Declare the class(es), possibly in a header file:
     namespace java {
       namespace lang {
         class Object;
         class String;
         ...
       }
     }
     
     class java::lang::String : public java::lang::Object
     {
       ...
     };

The @{b}gcjh@{ub} tool automatically generates the necessary namespace
declarations.

Leaving out package names
-------------------------

Always using the fully-qualified name of a java class can be tiresomely
verbose.  Using the full qualified name also ties the code to a single
package making code changes necessary should the class move from one
package to another.  The Java @{b}package@{ub} declaration specifies that the
following class declarations are in the named package, without having
to explicitly name the full package qualifiers.  The @{b}package@{ub}
declaration can be followed by zero or more @{b}import@{ub} declarations, which
allows either a single class or all the classes in a package to be
named by a simple identifier.  C++ provides something similar with the
@{b}using@{ub} declaration and directive.

In Java:

     import PACKAGE-NAME.CLASS-NAME;

allows the program text to refer to CLASS-NAME as a shorthand for the
fully qualified name: @{b}PACKAGE-NAME.CLASS-NAME@{ub}.

To achieve the same effect C++, you have to do this:

     using PACKAGE-NAME::CLASS-NAME;

Java can also cause imports on demand, like this:

     import PACKAGE-NAME.*;

Doing this allows any class from the package PACKAGE-NAME to be
referred to only by its class-name within the program text.

The same effect can be achieved in C++ like this:

     using namespace PACKAGE-NAME;

@endnode

@node "Primitive types" "gcj.guide/Primitive types"
@next "Interfaces"
@prev "Packages"
@toc "About CNI"

Primitive types
===============

Java provides 8 @{i}primitives@{ui} types which represent integers, floats,
characters and booleans (and also the void type).  C++ has its own very
similar concrete types.  Such types in C++ however are not always
implemented in the same way (an int might be 16, 32 or 64 bits for
example) so CNI provides a special C++ type for each primitive Java
type:

@{b}Java type@{ub}@{b}C/C++ typename@{ub}@{b}Description@{ub}
@{b}char@{ub}  @{b}jchar@{ub}     16 bit Unicode character
@{b}boolean@{ub}@{b}jboolean@{ub}  logical (true or false) values
@{b}byte@{ub}  @{b}jbyte@{ub}     8-bit signed integer
@{b}short@{ub} @{b}jshort@{ub}    16 bit signed integer
@{b}int@{ub}   @{b}jint@{ub}      32 bit signed integer
@{b}long@{ub}  @{b}jlong@{ub}     64 bit signed integer
@{b}float@{ub} @{b}jfloat@{ub}    32 bit IEEE floating point number
@{b}double@{ub}@{b}jdouble@{ub}   64 bit IEEE floating point number
@{b}void@{ub}  @{b}void@{ub}      no value

   When referring to a Java type You should always use these C++
typenames (e.g.: @{b}jint@{ub}) to avoid disappointment.

Reference types associated with primitive types
-----------------------------------------------

In Java each primitive type has an associated reference type, e.g.:
@{b}boolean@{ub} has an associated @{b}java.lang.Boolean@{ub} class.  In order to make
working with such classes easier GCJ provides the macro @{b}JvPrimClass@{ub}:

 - macro: JvPrimClass type
     Return a pointer to the @{b}Class@{ub} object corresponding to the type
     supplied.

          JvPrimClass(void) => java.lang.Void.TYPE


@endnode

@node "Interfaces" "gcj.guide/Interfaces"
@next "Objects and Classes"
@prev "Primitive types"
@toc "About CNI"

Interfaces
==========

A Java class can @{i}implement@{ui} zero or more @{i}interfaces@{ui}, in addition to
inheriting from a single base class.

   CNI allows CNI code to implement methods of interfaces.  You can
also call methods through interface references, with some limitations.

   CNI doesn't understand interface inheritance at all yet.  So, you
can only call an interface method when the declared type of the field
being called matches the interface which declares that method.  The
workaround is to cast the interface reference to the right
superinterface.

   For example if you have:

     interface A
     {
       void a();
     }
     
     interface B extends A
     {
       void b();
     }

   and declare a variable of type @{b}B@{ub} in C++, you can't call @{b}a()@{ub} unless
you cast it to an @{b}A@{ub} first.

@endnode

@node "Objects and Classes" "gcj.guide/Objects and Classes"
@next "Class Initialization"
@prev "Interfaces"
@toc "About CNI"

Objects and Classes
===================

Classes
-------

All Java classes are derived from @{b}java.lang.Object@{ub}.  C++ does not have
a unique root class, but we use the C++ class @{b}java::lang::Object@{ub} as the
C++ version of the @{b}java.lang.Object@{ub} Java class.  All other Java classes
are mapped into corresponding C++ classes derived from
@{b}java::lang::Object@{ub}.

   Interface inheritance (the @{b}implements@{ub} keyword) is currently not
reflected in the C++ mapping.

Object fields
-------------

Each object contains an object header, followed by the instance fields
of the class, in order.  The object header consists of a single pointer
to a dispatch or virtual function table.  (There may be extra fields @{i}in
front of@{ui} the object, for example for memory management, but this is
invisible to the application, and the reference to the object points to
the dispatch table pointer.)

   The fields are laid out in the same order, alignment, and size as in
C++.  Specifically, 8-bite and 16-bit native types (@{b}byte@{ub}, @{b}short@{ub}, @{b}char@{ub},
and @{b}boolean@{ub}) are @{i}not@{ui} widened to 32 bits.  Note that the Java VM does
extend 8-bit and 16-bit types to 32 bits when on the VM stack or
temporary registers.

   If you include the @{b}gcjh@{ub}-generated header for a class, you can access
fields of Java classes in the @{i}natural@{ui} way.  For example, given the
following Java class:

     public class Int
     {
       public int i;
       public Integer (int i) { this.i = i; }
       public static zero = new Integer(0);
     }

   you can write:

     #include <gcj/cni.h>;
     #include <Int>;
     
     Int*
     mult (Int *p, jint k)
     {
       if (k == 0)
         return Int::zero;  // Static member access.
       return new Int(p->i * k);
     }

Access specifiers
-----------------

CNI does not strictly enforce the Java access specifiers, because Java
permissions cannot be directly mapped into C++ permission.  Private
Java fields and methods are mapped to private C++ fields and methods,
but other fields and methods are mapped to public fields and methods.

@endnode

@node "Class Initialization" "gcj.guide/Class Initialization"
@next "Object allocation"
@prev "Objects and Classes"
@toc "About CNI"

Class Initialization
====================

Java requires that each class be automatically initialized at the time
of the first active use.  Initializing a class involves initializing
the static fields, running code in class initializer methods, and
initializing base classes.  There may also be some implementation
specific actions, such as allocating @{b}String@{ub} objects corresponding to
string literals in the code.

   The GCJ compiler inserts calls to @{b}JvInitClass@{ub} at appropriate places
to ensure that a class is initialized when required.  The C++ compiler
does not insert these calls automatically--it is the programmer's
responsibility to make sure classes are initialized.  However, this is
fairly painless because of the conventions assumed by the Java system.

   First, @{b}libgcj@{ub} will make sure a class is initialized before an
instance of that object is created.  This is one of the
responsibilities of the @{b}new@{ub} operation.  This is taken care of both in
Java code, and in C++ code.  When G++ sees a @{b}new@{ub} of a Java class, it
will call a routine in @{b}libgcj@{ub} to allocate the object, and that routine
will take care of initializing the class.  Note however that this does
not happen for Java arrays; you must allocate those using the
appropriate CNI function.  It follows that you can access an instance
field, or call an instance (non-static) method and be safe in the
knowledge that the class and all of its base classes have been
initialized.

   Invoking a static method is also safe.  This is because the Java
compiler adds code to the start of a static method to make sure the
class is initialized.  However, the C++ compiler does not add this
extra code.  Hence, if you write a native static method using CNI, you
are responsible for calling @{b}JvInitClass@{ub} before doing anything else in
the method (unless you are sure it is safe to leave it out).

   Accessing a static field also requires the class of the field to be
initialized.  The Java compiler will generate code to call @{b}Jv_InitClass@{ub}
before getting or setting the field.  However, the C++ compiler will
not generate this extra code, so it is your responsibility to make sure
the class is initialized before you access a static field from C++.

@endnode

@node "Object allocation" "gcj.guide/Object allocation"
@next "Arrays"
@prev "Class Initialization"
@toc "About CNI"

Object allocation
=================

New Java objects are allocated using a @{i}class instance creation
expression@{ui}, e.g.:

     new TYPE ( ... )

   The same syntax is used in C++.  The main difference is that C++
objects have to be explicitly deleted; in Java they are automatically
deleted by the garbage collector.  Using CNI, you can allocate a new
Java object using standard C++ syntax and the C++ compiler will allocate
memory from the garbage collector.  If you have overloaded
constructors, the compiler will choose the correct one using standard
C++ overload resolution rules.

For example:

     java::util::Hashtable *ht = new java::util::Hashtable(120);

 - Function: void* _Jv_AllocBytes (jsize SIZE)
     Allocates SIZE bytes from the heap.  The memory is not scanned by
     the garbage collector but it freed if no references to it are
     discovered.

@endnode

@node "Arrays" "gcj.guide/Arrays"
@next "Methods"
@prev "Object allocation"
@toc "About CNI"

Arrays
======

While in many ways Java is similar to C and C++, it is quite different
in its treatment of arrays.  C arrays are based on the idea of pointer
arithmetic, which would be incompatible with Java's security
requirements.  Java arrays are true objects (array types inherit from
@{b}java.lang.Object@{ub}).  An array-valued variable is one that contains a
reference (pointer) to an array object.

   Referencing a Java array in C++ code is done using the @{b}JArray@{ub}
template, which as defined as follows:

     class __JArray : public java::lang::Object
     {
     public:
       int length;
     };
     
     template<class T>
     class JArray : public __JArray
     {
       T data[0];
     public:
       T& operator[](jint i) { return data[i]; }
     };

   There are a number of @{b}typedef@{ub}s which correspond to @{b}typedef@{ub}s from the
JNI.  Each is the type of an array holding objects of the relevant type:

     typedef __JArray *jarray;
     typedef JArray<jobject> *jobjectArray;
     typedef JArray<jboolean> *jbooleanArray;
     typedef JArray<jbyte> *jbyteArray;
     typedef JArray<jchar> *jcharArray;
     typedef JArray<jshort> *jshortArray;
     typedef JArray<jint> *jintArray;
     typedef JArray<jlong> *jlongArray;
     typedef JArray<jfloat> *jfloatArray;
     typedef JArray<jdouble> *jdoubleArray;

 - Method on template<class T>: T* elements (JArray<T> ARRAY)
     This template function can be used to get a pointer to the
     elements of the @{b}array@{ub}.  For instance, you can fetch a pointer to
     the integers that make up an @{b}int[]@{ub} like so:

          extern jintArray foo;
          jint *intp = elements (foo);

     The name of this function may change in the future.

 - Function: jobjectArray JvNewObjectArray (jsize LENGTH, jclass KLASS,
          jobject INIT)
     Here @{b}klass@{ub} is the type of elements of the array and @{b}init@{ub} is the
     initial value put into every slot in the array.

Creating arrays
---------------

For each primitive type there is a function which can be used to create
a new array of that type.  The name of the function is of the form:

     JvNewTYPEArray

For example:

     JvNewBooleanArray

can be used to create an array of Java primitive boolean types.

The following function definition is the template for all such
functions:

 - Function: jbooleanArray JvNewBooleanArray (jint LENGTH)
     Create's an array LENGTH indices long.

 - Function: jsize JvGetArrayLength (jarray ARRAY)
     Returns the length of the ARRAY.

@endnode

@node "Methods" "gcj.guide/Methods"
@next "Strings"
@prev "Arrays"
@toc "About CNI"

Methods
=======

Java methods are mapped directly into C++ methods.  The header files
generated by @{b}gcjh@{ub} include the appropriate method definitions.
Basically, the generated methods have the same names and @{i}corresponding@{ui}
types as the Java methods, and are called in the natural manner.

Overloading
-----------

Both Java and C++ provide method overloading, where multiple methods in
a class have the same name, and the correct one is chosen (at compile
time) depending on the argument types.  The rules for choosing the
correct method are (as expected) more complicated in C++ than in Java,
but given a set of overloaded methods generated by @{b}gcjh@{ub} the C++
compiler will choose the expected one.

   Common assemblers and linkers are not aware of C++ overloading, so
the standard implementation strategy is to encode the parameter types
of a method into its assembly-level name.  This encoding is called
@{i}mangling@{ui}, and the encoded name is the @{i}mangled name@{ui}.  The same mechanism
is used to implement Java overloading.  For C++/Java interoperability,
it is important that both the Java and C++ compilers use the @{i}same@{ui}
encoding scheme.

Static methods
--------------

Static Java methods are invoked in CNI using the standard C++ syntax,
using the @{b}::@{ub} operator rather than the @{b}.@{ub} operator.

For example:

     jint i = java::lang::Math::round((jfloat) 2.3);

C++ method definition syntax is used to define a static native method.
For example:

     #include <java/lang/Integer>
     java::lang::Integer*
     java::lang::Integer::getInteger(jstring str)
     {
       ...
     }

Object Constructors
-------------------

Constructors are called implicitly as part of object allocation using
the @{b}new@{ub} operator.

For example:

     java::lang::Integer *x = new java::lang::Integer(234);

   Java does not allow a constructor to be a native method.  This
limitation can be coded round however because a constructor can @{i}call@{ui} a
native method.

Instance methods
----------------

Calling a Java instance method from a C++ CNI method is done using the
standard C++ syntax, e.g.:

     // First create the Java object.
     java::lang::Integer *x = new java::lang::Integer(234);
     // Now call a method.
     jint prim_value = x->intValue();
     if (x->longValue == 0)
       ...

Defining a Java native instance method is also done the natural way:

     #include <java/lang/Integer.h>
     
     jdouble
     java::lang:Integer::doubleValue()
     {
       return (jdouble) value;
     }

Interface methods
-----------------

In Java you can call a method using an interface reference.  This is
supported, but not completely.  See @{"Interfaces" link "Interfaces"}.

@endnode

@node "Strings" "gcj.guide/Strings"
@next "Mixing with C++"
@prev "Methods"
@toc "About CNI"

Strings
=======

CNI provides a number of utility functions for working with Java Java
@{b}String@{ub} objects.  The names and interfaces are analogous to those of JNI.

 - Function: jstring JvNewString (const char* CHARS, jsize LEN)
     Returns a Java @{b}String@{ub} object with characters from the C string
     CHARS up to the index LEN in that array.

 - Function: jstring JvNewStringLatin1 (const char* BYTES, jsize LEN)
     Returns a Java @{b}String@{ub} made up of LEN bytes from BYTES.

 - Function: jstring JvNewStringLatin1 (const char* BYTES)
     As above but the length of the @{b}String@{ub} is @{b}strlen(BYTES)@{ub}.

 - Function: jstring JvNewStringUTF (const char* BYTES)
     Returns a @{b}String@{ub} which is made up of the UTF encoded characters
     present in the C string BYTES.

 - Function: jchar* JvGetStringChars (jstring STR)
     Returns a pointer to an array of characters making up the @{b}String@{ub}
     STR.

 - Function: int JvGetStringUTFLength (jstring STR)
     Returns the number of bytes required to encode the contents of the
     @{b}String@{ub} STR in UTF-8.

 - Function: jsize JvGetStringUTFRegion (jstring STR, jsize START,
          jsize LEN, char* BUF)
     Puts the UTF-8 encoding of a region of the @{b}String@{ub} STR into the
     buffer @{b}buf@{ub}.  The region to fetch is marked by START and LEN.

     Note that BUF is a buffer, not a C string.  It is @{i}not@{ui} null
     terminated.

@endnode

@node "Mixing with C++" "gcj.guide/Mixing with C++"
@next "Exception Handling"
@prev "Strings"
@toc "About CNI"

Interoperating with C/C++
=========================

Because CNI is designed to represent Java classes and methods it cannot
be mixed readily with C/C++ types.

   One important restriction is that Java classes cannot have non-Java
type instance or static variables and cannot have methods which take
non-Java types as arguments or return non-Java types.

None of the following is possible with CNI:


     class ::MyClass : public java::lang::Object
     {
        char* variable;  // char* is not a valid Java type.
     }
     
     
     uint
     ::SomeClass::someMethod (char *arg)
     {
       .
       .
       .
     }   // @{b}uint@{ub} is not a valid Java type, neither is @{b}char*@{ub}

Of course, it is ok to use C/C++ types within the scope of a method:

     jint
     ::SomeClass::otherMethod (jstring str)
     {
        char *arg = ...
        .
        .
        .
     }

   But this restriction can cause a problem so CNI includes the
@{b}gnu.gcj.RawData@{ub} class.  The @{b}RawData@{ub} class is a @{i}non-scanned reference@{ui}
type.  In other words variables declared of type @{b}RawData@{ub} can contain
any data and are not checked by the compiler in any way.

   This means that you can put C/C++ data structures (including classes)
in your CNI classes, as long as you use the appropriate cast.

Here are some examples:


     class ::MyClass : public java::lang::Object
     {
        gnu.gcj.RawData string;
     
        MyClass ();
        gnu.gcj.RawData getText ();
        void printText ();
     }
     
     ::MyClass::MyClass ()
     {
        char* text = ...
        string = text;
     }
     
     gnu.gcj.RawData
     ::MyClass::getText ()
     {
        return string;
     }
     
     void
     ::MyClass::printText ()
     {
       printf("%s\\n", (char*) string);
     }

@endnode

@node "Exception Handling" "gcj.guide/Exception Handling"
@next "Synchronization"
@prev "Mixing with C++"
@toc "About CNI"

Exception Handling
==================

While C++ and Java share a common exception handling framework, things
are not yet perfectly integrated.  The main issue is that the run-time
type information facilities of the two languages are not integrated.

   Still, things work fairly well.  You can throw a Java exception from
C++ using the ordinary @{b}throw@{ub} construct, and this exception can be
caught by Java code.  Similarly, you can catch an exception thrown from
Java using the C++ @{b}catch@{ub} construct.

Here is an example:

     if (i >= count)
        throw new java::lang::IndexOutOfBoundsException();

   Normally, G++ will automatically detect when you are writing C++
code that uses Java exceptions, and handle them appropriately.
However, if C++ code only needs to execute destructors when Java
exceptions are thrown through it, GCC will guess incorrectly.  Sample
problematic code:

     struct S { ~S(); };
     
     extern void bar();    // Is implemented in Java and may throw exceptions.
     
     void foo()
     {
       S s;
       bar();
     }

   The usual effect of an incorrect guess is a link failure,
complaining of a missing routine called @{b}__gxx_personality_v0@{ub}.

   You can inform the compiler that Java exceptions are to be used in a
translation unit, irrespective of what it might think, by writing
@{b}#pragma GCC java_exceptions@{ub} at the head of the file.  This @{b}#pragma@{ub} must
appear before any functions that throw or catch exceptions, or run
destructors when exceptions are thrown through them.

@endnode

@node "Synchronization" "gcj.guide/Synchronization"
@next "Invocation"
@prev "Exception Handling"
@toc "About CNI"

Synchronization
===============

Each Java object has an implicit monitor.  The Java VM uses the
instruction @{b}monitorenter@{ub} to acquire and lock a monitor, and @{b}monitorexit@{ub}
to release it.

   The corresponding CNI macros are @{b}JvMonitorEnter@{ub} and @{b}JvMonitorExit@{ub}
(JNI has similar  methods @{b}MonitorEnter@{ub} and @{b}MonitorExit@{ub}).

   The Java source language does not provide direct access to these
primitives.  Instead, there is a @{b}synchronized@{ub} statement that does an
implicit @{b}monitorenter@{ub} before entry to the block, and does a @{b}monitorexit@{ub}
on exit from the block.  Note that the lock has to be released even
when the block is abnormally terminated by an exception, which means
there is an implicit @{b}try finally@{ub} surrounding synchronization locks.

   From C++, it makes sense to use a destructor to release a lock.  CNI
defines the following utility class:

     class JvSynchronize() {
       jobject obj;
       JvSynchronize(jobject o) { obj = o; JvMonitorEnter(o); }
       ~JvSynchronize() { JvMonitorExit(obj); }
     };

   So this Java code:

     synchronized (OBJ)
     {
        CODE
     }

might become this C++ code:

     {
        JvSynchronize dummy (OBJ);
        CODE;
     }

   Java also has methods with the @{b}synchronized@{ub} attribute.  This is
equivalent to wrapping the entire method body in a @{b}synchronized@{ub}
statement.  (Alternatively, an implementation could require the caller
to do the synchronization.  This is not practical for a compiler,
because each virtual method call would have to test at run-time if
synchronization is needed.)  Since in @{b}gcj@{ub} the @{b}synchronized@{ub} attribute is
handled by the method implementation, it is up to the programmer of a
synchronized native method to handle the synchronization (in the C++
implementation of the method).  In other words, you need to manually
add @{b}JvSynchronize@{ub} in a @{b}native synchronized@{ub} method.

@endnode

@node "Invocation" "gcj.guide/Invocation"
@next "Reflection"
@prev "Synchronization"
@toc "About CNI"

Invocation
==========

CNI permits C++ applications to make calls into Java classes, in
addition to allowing Java code to call into C++. Several functions,
known as the @{i}invocation API@{ui}, are provided to support this.

 - Function: jint JvCreateJavaVM (void* VM_ARGS)
     Initializes the Java runtime. This function performs essential
     initialization of the threads interface, garbage collector,
     exception handling and other key aspects of the runtime. It must
     be called once by an application with a non-Java @{b}main()@{ub} function,
     before any other Java or CNI calls are made.  It is safe, but not
     recommended, to call @{b}JvCreateJavaVM()@{ub} more than once provided it
     is only called from a single thread.  The VMARGS parameter can be
     used to specify initialization parameters for the Java runtime. It
     may be @{b}NULL@{ub}.  This function returns @{b}0@{ub} upon success, or @{b}-1@{ub} if the
     runtime is already initialized.

     @{i}Note:@{ui} In GCJ 3.1, the @{b}vm_args@{ub} parameter is ignored. It may be used
     in a future release.

 - Function: java::lang::Thread* JvAttachCurrentThread (jstring NAME,
          java::lang::ThreadGroup* GROUP)
     Registers an existing thread with the Java runtime.  This must be
     called once from each thread, before that thread makes any other
     Java or CNI calls. It must be called after @{b}JvCreateJavaVM@{ub}.  NAME
     specifies a name for the thread. It may be @{b}NULL@{ub}, in which case a
     name will be generated.  GROUP is the ThreadGroup in which this
     thread will be a member. If it is @{b}NULL@{ub}, the thread will be a
     member of the main thread group.  The return value is the Java
     @{b}Thread@{ub} object that represents the thread.  It is safe to call
     @{b}JvAttachCurrentThread()@{ub} more than once from the same thread. If
     the thread is already attached, the call is ignored and the current
     thread object is returned.

 - Function: jint JvDetachCurrentThread ()
     Unregisters a thread from the Java runtime. This should be called
     by threads that were attached using @{b}JvAttachCurrentThread()@{ub}, after
     they have finished making calls to Java code. This ensures that
     any resources associated with the thread become eligible for
     garbage collection.  This function returns @{b}0@{ub} upon success, or @{b}-1@{ub}
     if the current thread is not attached.

Handling uncaught exceptions
----------------------------

If an exception is thrown from Java code called using the invocation
API, and no handler for the exception can be found, the runtime will
abort the application. In order to make the application more robust, it
is recommended that code which uses the invocation API be wrapped by a
top-level try/catch block that catches all Java exceptions.

Example
-------

The following code demonstrates the use of the invocation API. In this
example, the C++ application initializes the Java runtime and attaches
itself. The @{b}java.lang.System@{ub} class is initialized in order to access
its @{b}out@{ub} field, and a Java string is printed. Finally, the thread is
detached from the runtime once it has finished making Java calls.
Everything is wrapped with a try/catch block to provide a default
handler for any uncaught exceptions.

   The example can be compiled with @{b}c++ test.cc -lgcj@{ub}.

     // test.cc
     #include <gcj/cni.h>
     #include <java/lang/System.h>
     #include <java/io/PrintStream.h>
     #include <java/lang/Throwable.h>
     
     int main(int argc, char *argv)
     {
       using namespace java::lang;
     
       try
       {
         JvCreateJavaVM(NULL);
         JvAttachCurrentThread(NULL, NULL);
     
         String *message = JvNewStringLatin1("Hello from C++");
         JvInitClass(&System::class$);
         System::out->println(message);
     
         JvDetachCurrentThread();
       }
       catch (Throwable *t)
       {
         System::err->println(JvNewStringLatin1("Unhandled Java exception:"));
         t->printStackTrace();
       }
     }

@endnode

@node "Reflection" "gcj.guide/Reflection"
@prev "Invocation"
@toc "About CNI"

Reflection
==========

Reflection is possible with CNI code, it functions similarly to how it
functions with JNI.

   The types @{b}jfieldID@{ub} and @{b}jmethodID@{ub} are as in JNI.

The functions:

   * @{b}JvFromReflectedField@{ub},

   * @{b}JvFromReflectedMethod@{ub},

   * @{b}JvToReflectedField@{ub}

   * @{b}JvToFromReflectedMethod@{ub}

will be added shortly, as will other functions corresponding to JNI.

@endnode

@node "System properties" "gcj.guide/System properties"
@next "Resources"
@prev "About CNI"
@toc "Main"

System properties
*****************

The runtime behavior of the @{b}libgcj@{ub} library can be modified by setting
certain system properties.  These properties can be compiled into the
program using the @{b}-DNAME[=VALUE]@{ub} option to @{b}gcj@{ub} or by setting them
explicitly in the program by calling the @{b}java.lang.System.setProperty()@{ub}
method.  Some system properties are only used for informational
purposes (like giving a version number or a user name).  A program can
inspect the current value of a property by calling the
@{b}java.lang.System.getProperty()@{ub} method.


 @{" Standard Properties        " link "Standard Properties"}  Standard properties supported by @{b}libgcj@{ub}
 @{" GNU Classpath Properties   " link "GNU Classpath Properties"}  Properties found in Classpath based libraries
 @{" libgcj Runtime Properties  " link "libgcj Runtime Properties"}  Properties specific to @{b}libgcj@{ub}

@endnode

@node "Standard Properties" "gcj.guide/Standard Properties"
@next "GNU Classpath Properties"
@toc "System properties"

Standard Properties
===================

The following properties are normally found in all implementations of
the core libraries for the Java language.

@{b}java.version@{ub}
     The @{b}libgcj@{ub} version number.

@{b}java.vendor@{ub}
     Set to @{b}The Free Software Foundation, Inc.@{ub}

@{b}java.vendor.url@{ub}
     Set to `http://gcc.gnu.org/java/'.

@{b}java.home@{ub}
     The directory where @{b}gcj@{ub} was installed.  Taken from the @{b}--prefix@{ub}
     option given to @{b}configure@{ub}.

@{b}java.class.version@{ub}
     The class format version number supported by the libgcj byte code
     interpreter.  (Currently @{b}46.0@{ub})

@{b}java.vm.specification.version@{ub}
     The Virtual Machine Specification version implemented by @{b}libgcj@{ub}.
     (Currently @{b}1.0@{ub})

@{b}java.vm.specification.vendor@{ub}
     The name of the Virtual Machine specification designer.

@{b}java.vm.specification.name@{ub}
     The name of the Virtual Machine specification (Set to @{b}Java Virtual
     Machine Specification@{ub}).

@{b}java.vm.version@{ub}
     The @{b}gcj@{ub} version number.

@{b}java.vm.vendor@{ub}
     Set to @{b}The Free Software Foundation, Inc.@{ub}

@{b}java.vm.name@{ub}
     Set to @{b}GNU libgcj@{ub}.

@{b}java.specification.version@{ub}
     The Runtime Environment specification version implemented by
     @{b}libgcj@{ub}.  (Currently set to @{b}1.3@{ub})

@{b}java.specification.vendor@{ub}
     The Runtime Environment specification designer.

@{b}java.specification.name@{ub}
     The name of the Runtime Environment specification (Set to @{b}Java
     Platform API Specification@{ub}).

@{b}java.class.path@{ub}
     The paths (jar files, zip files and directories) used for finding
     class files.

@{b}java.library.path@{ub}
     Directory path used for finding native libraries.

@{b}java.io.tmpdir@{ub}
     The directory used to put temporary files in.

@{b}java.compiler@{ub}
     Name of the Just In Time compiler to use by the byte code
     interpreter.  Currently not used in @{b}libgcj@{ub}.

@{b}java.ext.dirs@{ub}
     Directories containing jar files with extra libraries.  Will be
     used when resolving classes.  Currently not used in @{b}libgcj@{ub}.

@{b}java.protocol.handler.pkgs@{ub}
     A @{b}|@{ub} separated list of package names that is used to find classes
     that implement handlers for @{b}java.net.URL@{ub}.

@{b}java.rmi.server.codebase@{ub}
     A list of URLs that is used by the @{b}java.rmi.server.RMIClassLoader@{ub}
     to load classes from.

@{b}jdbc.drivers@{ub}
     A list of class names that will be loaded by the
     @{b}java.sql.DriverManager@{ub} when it starts up.

@{b}file.separator@{ub}
     The separator used in when directories are included in a filename
     (normally @{b}/@{ub} or @{b}\\ @{ub} ).

@{b}file.encoding@{ub}
     The default character encoding used when converting platform
     native files to Unicode (usually set to @{b}8859_1@{ub}).

@{b}path.separator@{ub}
     The standard separator used when a string contains multiple paths
     (normally @{b}:@{ub} or @{b};@{ub}), the string is usually not a valid character to
     use in normal directory names.)

@{b}line.separator@{ub}
     The default line separator used on the platform (normally @{b}\\n@{ub}, @{b}\\r@{ub}
     or a combination of those two characters).

@{b}policy.provider@{ub}
     The class name used for the default policy provider returned by
     @{b}java.security.Policy.getPolicy@{ub}.

@{b}user.name@{ub}
     The name of the user running the program.  Can be the full name,
     the login name or empty if unknown.

@{b}user.home@{ub}
     The default directory to put user specific files in.

@{b}user.dir@{ub}
     The current working directory from which the program was started.

@{b}user.language@{ub}
     The default language as used by the @{b}java.util.Locale@{ub} class.

@{b}user.region@{ub}
     The default region as used by the @{b}java.util.Local@{ub} class.

@{b}user.variant@{ub}
     The default variant of the language and region local used.

@{b}user.timezone@{ub}
     The default timezone as used by the @{b}java.util.TimeZone@{ub} class.

@{b}os.name@{ub}
     The operating system/kernel name that the program runs on.

@{b}os.arch@{ub}
     The hardware that we are running on.

@{b}os.version@{ub}
     The version number of the operating system/kernel.

@{b}awt.appletWarning@{ub}
     The string to display when an untrusted applet is displayed.
     Returned by @{b}java.awt.Window.getWarningString()@{ub} when the window is
     "insecure".

@{b}awt.toolkit@{ub}
     The class name used for initializing the default @{b}java.awt.Toolkit@{ub}.
     Defaults to @{b}gnu.awt.gtk.GtkToolkit@{ub}.

@{b}http.proxyHost@{ub}
     Name of proxy host for http connections.

@{b}http.proxyPort@{ub}
     Port number to use when a proxy host is in use.


@endnode

@node "GNU Classpath Properties" "gcj.guide/GNU Classpath Properties"
@next "libgcj Runtime Properties"
@prev "Standard Properties"
@toc "System properties"

GNU Classpath Properties
========================

@{b}libgcj@{ub} is based on the GNU Classpath (Essential Libraries for Java) a
GNU project to create free core class libraries for use with virtual
machines and compilers for the Java language.  The following properties
are common to libraries based on GNU Classpath.

@{b}gcj.dumpobject@{ub}
     Enables printing serialization debugging by the
     @{b}java.io.ObjectInput@{ub} and @{b}java.io.ObjectOutput@{ub} classes when set to
     something else then the empty string.  Only used when running a
     debug build of the library.

@{b}gnu.classpath.vm.shortname@{ub}
     This is a succint name of the virtual machine.  For @{b}libgcj@{ub}, this
     will always be @{b}libgcj@{ub}.

@{b}gnu.classpath.home.url@{ub}
     A base URL used for finding system property files (e.g.,
     @{b}classpath.security@{ub}).  By default this is a @{b}file:@{ub} URL pointing to
     the @{b}lib@{ub} directory under @{b}java.home@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "libgcj Runtime Properties" "gcj.guide/libgcj Runtime Properties"
@prev "GNU Classpath Properties"
@toc "System properties"

libgcj Runtime Properties
=========================

The following properties are specific to the @{b}libgcj@{ub} runtime and will
normally not be found in other core libraries for the java language.

@{b}java.fullversion@{ub}
     The combination of @{b}java.vm.name@{ub} and @{b}java.vm.version@{ub}.

@{b}java.vm.info@{ub}
     Same as @{b}java.fullversion@{ub}.

@{b}impl.prefix@{ub}
     Used by the @{b}java.net.DatagramSocket@{ub} class when set to something
     else then the empty string.  When set all newly created
     @{b}DatagramSocket@{ub}s will try to load a class
     @{b}java.net.[impl.prefix]DatagramSocketImpl@{ub} instead of the normal
     @{b}java.net.PlainDatagramSocketImpl@{ub}.

@{b}gnu.gcj.progname@{ub}
     The name that was used to invoked the program.

@{b}gnu.gcj.runtime.NameFinder.demangle@{ub}
     Whether names in a stack trace should be demangled.  Defaults to
     @{b}true@{ub}.

@{b}gnu.gcj.runtime.NameFinder.sanitize@{ub}
     Whether calls to initialize exceptions and starting the runtime
     system should be removed from the stack trace.  Only done when
     names are demangled.  Defaults to @{b}true@{ub}.

@{b}gnu.gcj.runtime.NameFinder.remove_unknown@{ub}
     Whether calls to unknown functions (class and method names are
     unknown) should be removed from the stack trace.  Only done when
     the stack is sanitized.  Ignored if this means no stack trace
     information would be available anymore.  Defaults to @{b}true@{ub}.

@{b}gnu.gcj.runtime.NameFinder.remove_interpreter@{ub}
     Whether runtime interpreter calls (methods in the @{b}_Jv_InterpMethod@{ub}
     class and functions starting with @{b}ffi_@{ub}) should be removed from the
     stack trace.  Only done when the stack is sanitized.  Defaults to
     @{b}true@{ub}.

@{b}gnu.gcj.runtime.NameFinder.use_addr2line@{ub}
     Whether an external process (@{b}addr2line@{ub} or @{b}addr2name.awk@{ub}) should be
     used as fallback to convert the addresses to function names when
     the runtime is unable to do it through @{b}dladdr@{ub}.

@{b}gnu.gcj.runtime.VMClassLoader.library_control@{ub}
     This controls how shared libraries are automatically loaded by the
     built-in class loader.  By default, or if this property is set to
     @{b}full@{ub}, a full search is done for each requested class.  If this
     property is set to @{b}cache@{ub}, then any failed lookups are cached and
     not tried again.  If this property is set to @{b}never@{ub}, then lookups
     are never done.  For more information, See @{"Extensions" link "Extensions"}.


@endnode

@node "Resources" "gcj.guide/Resources"
@prev "System properties"
@toc "Main"

Resources
*********

While writing @{b}gcj@{ub} and @{b}libgcj@{ub} we have, of course, relied heavily on
documentation from Sun Microsystems.  In particular we have used The
Java Language Specification (both first and second editions), the Java
Class Libraries (volumes one and two), and the Java Virtual Machine
Specification.  In addition we've used the online documentation at
`http://java.sun.com/'.

   The current @{b}gcj@{ub} home page is `http://gcc.gnu.org/java/'.

   For more information on gcc, see `http://gcc.gnu.org/'.

   Some @{b}libgcj@{ub} testing is done using the Mauve test suite.  This is a
free software Java class library test suite which is being written
because the JCK is not free.  See `http://sources.redhat.com/mauve/'
for more information.

@endnode

